# **Overview**

In this assignment, you will design and test your own agentic workflow to solve a problem or pain point you are facing at work or in your personal life. Your system must include an ensemble of several skills/actions, and you will evaluate it using a mini-benchmark you design.

You may implement your system in any of the following ways:

* Markdown skill/agentic set designed to work together in Codex, Cloud, or any LLM assistant

* n8n workflow (or equivalent such as Google Opal, Relay.app/Stack.ai, etc.).

Your goal is to experience what it actually feels like to build and evaluate a small agentic system from scratch, then assess whether it is truly useful in practice. If relevant, you may repurpose your course project idea for HW2.

# **Learning Objectives**

By completing this assignment, you will:

* Design a real-world agentic workflow from scratch

* Connect multiple skills/agents into a coherent system

* Practice prompt design and improvement based on actual usage

* Build and run a rigorous mini benchmark to evaluate performance

* Critically assess usefulness, limitations, and tradeoffs

**A Note on Why This Assignment Is Open-Ended**

This homework is intentionally broad. There are countless workflows one could build, and I made a deliberate design choice to let you pursue whichever one matters most to you. The alternative â€” having every student replicate the same predefined workflow â€” would certainly teach that one specific thing, but it would also constrain the path so much that the lessons become harder to generalize. At its core, working with AI is about building mental models: understanding how AI succeeds, where it struggles, and how to orchestrate it effectively. By choosing your own workflow, you will each encounter different challenges and different difficulties â€” and that is exactly the point.

If I were to attempt every one of your workflows myself, I would run into bottlenecks, too. In fact, as an exercise, I tried to build some of the workflows you suggested in class, and it wasn't always easy. I had to iterate, abandon some approaches, and try alternatives before learning which ones were truly suitable. That process of discovery is what this assignment is designed to teach. Whenever you have a little time to spare, I encourage you to keep experimenting on your own â€” it compounds quickly. I also highly recommend reading this blog post by Ethan Mollick: [Management as AI Superpower](https://www.oneusefulthing.org/p/management-as-ai-superpower).

| Path A: Skills Pack (Markdown files) Create a reusable set of skills as Markdown files (2-5 skills recommended) that can work standalone when installed. You may use Claude, OpenAI, or any other LLM to define and test the skills. âœ¨ Bonus (1 point): include an MCP tool. *Each skill file can typically include:* Skill name and purpose Inputs and outputs Step-by-step behavior Constraints and failure modes Example usage You will find an example of a skill markdown in Appendix. You can use the built-in skill creator in your preferred model (Claude, Codex, and Gemini CLI all include one). Simply activate it and describe your intent in natural language â€” the model will interview you to fill in the details. As a best practice, define what success looks like, what context the skill should check, and provide template answers where possible. Note: Skills and their integration with models are still very new, so occasional failures are expected. This is part of the learning process. If something goes wrong, it may mean the workflow isnâ€™t well suited for skills yet, or that the skill needs to be redesigned to handle more edge cases. Your grade is based on the quality of your attempt, your adherence to good practices, and your ability to reflect on outcomes â€” not on whether everything works perfectly. Keep in mind that not every workflow is a good fit for skills today (though this is improving rapidly). For example, suppose you want a system that checks your calendar for deadlines and sends you a reminder email. You could build this with skills and MCPs, but it would only run while your computer is on. If you need it to run automatically in the background â€” even when your machine is offline â€” a tool like n8n is a better choice, since it can deploy to a dedicated server. Before choosing your approach, ask yourself: Do I want a workflow I launch on demand from my own machine? Or do I need something fully automated that runs independently and can be shared with others via a link? Skills work well for personal, on-demand workflows, but sharing them across multiple computers is still somewhat limited. This is improving quickly, so consider your needs today and choose the path that fits best. |

## **Part 3: Real Usage \+ Iteration**

Run your system on at least two real tasks and keep track of:

* The inputs you used

* The outputs produced

* What you changed after the first few runs

* Whether the system helped or not

* Where it failed, hallucinated, or slowed you down

## **Part 4: Rigorous Mini Benchmark** 

You must design a mini-benchmark to test your system's performance. This is one of the most important parts for a successful agent.

**Your benchmark can include:**

* 2+ test cases that reflect the real task

* At least one baseline comparison (single-prompt LLM or your own manual process) if relevant for your workflow (e.g.,  generating a blogpost, a linkedin post, a cover letter). 

* Metrics you define (accuracy, time saved, hallucination rate, clarity, actionability, etc.)

* A scoring rubric (0-1 or 1-5 scale) with brief anchors

* Summary results and failure analysis if any

* At least 2 concrete examples in your tutorial write-up (show inputs and outputs)

You may use any evaluation method you prefer (human scoring, LLM-as-judge, automated checks, or a mix). There is no penalty for the method you choose, as long as it is clear and consistent.

# **Tutorial Write-Up Guidelines**

Your main written deliverable is a tutorial in PDF format. Write it so that someone who has never seen your workflow could follow your instructions and successfully replicate your agent from scratch. Think of every bottleneck you encountered, every question you had to answer along the way, and every decision that was not obvious â€” then make sure your tutorial addresses all of them.

**Start with the problem.** Begin your tutorial by clearly describing what you are trying to solve: the pain point, the current status quo, and why an agentic workflow is a promising approach. This gives your reader the context they need before diving into the technical details. Briefly outline what your workflow will do, and what the tech stack is for this tutorial.

**Document your system, depending on your path:**

*If you chose Path A (Skills Pack):*

* Provide a brief overview of each skill: its name, its purpose, and a one- or two-sentence summary of what it does.

* Include the exact prompts or instructions embedded in each skill file (in Appendix or inside the tutorial if relevant for discussion).

* Document at least one prompt iteration: what you changed, why you changed it, and whether it improved the output.

* Offer a brief critique of your prompt quality (clarity, constraints, tone, and evaluation criteria).

*If you chose Path B (n8n / SDK Workflow):*

* Include a screenshot or diagram of your workflow so the reader can see the overall structure at a glance.

* Document every prompt you used within the workflow nodes, so that someone could recreate the exact same pipeline.

* Document at least one prompt iteration: what you changed, why you changed it, and whether it improved the output.

* Offer a brief critique of your prompt quality (clarity, constraints, tone, and evaluation criteria).

**Document your building process.** Feel free to include as many figures, screenshots, and details as you like. For example: which tools and LLMs did you use? What prompts did you give to build or refine the system? How long did each step take? What were the frustrating parts? The more transparent you are, the more useful your tutorial will be.

**Benchmarking.** Dedicate a meaningful portion of your tutorial to explaining how you tested your system. Describe how you designed your benchmark, how you ran it, and what the results tell you about the quality of your agent. Refer to Appendix 2 for suggested evaluation methods.

**Reflection Prompts**

Here are elements you can discuss in your write-up (choose on what is relevant):

* Why this workflow, and why it matters

* What worked well vs. what did not

* How your prompts evolved and why

* What your benchmark revealed

* Would you keep using this system? Why or why not

**Sharing your work.** Include direct links to your system so that someone could replicate or try it (Canvas will also ask you for these links separately). For example, you could create a GitHub repository, host your files on Google Drive, or share a direct link to your workflow. After the course ends, I will invite you to optionally open-source your tutorial and code so we can showcase our collective creations and let others â€” both classmates and beyond â€” benefit from your work.

\# MSIS Homework Generator

\#\# Overview

Generate student-facing homework prompts aligned to the syllabus modules and learning objectives. Match the tone, structure, and rubric style of HW1 while adapting to the new topic and requirements.

\#\# Workflow

1\. Intake the quick prompt.  
\- Extract: course (MSIS 549 vs MSIS 522), homework number, topic/module, intended skills, estimated time, due date (if any), deliverable types, and grading weight or points.  
\- If any of these are missing, proceed with a draft and include an explicit Assumptions section plus 2-4 concise clarification questions at the end.

2\. Load course context.  
\- Read the current syllabus and HW1 prompt from the workspace using the paths in \`references/course-files.md\`.  
\- If either file is missing, ask the user for the correct path before drafting.

3\. Derive constraints and style anchors.  
\- Capture the relevant module, learning objectives, and expected rigor from the syllabus.  
\- Mirror HW1 structure: Overview, Learning Objectives, Assignment parts, Testing/Feedback (if relevant), optional research component, reflection blog post (if relevant), Deliverables, Rubric.  
\- Keep requirements measurable and student-friendly.

4\. Draft the assignment.  
\- Use the template in \`references/assignment-template.md\`.  
\- Make deliverables explicit and graded.  
\- Include a rubric table whose points sum to the requested total (default: 15 points).  
\- Ensure the workload matches the estimated time window.

5\. Quality checks.  
\- Verify alignment with the specified module and skills.  
\- Ensure each requirement is testable and not ambiguous.  
\- Avoid nested bullet lists unless absolutely necessary.  
\- If assumptions were made, highlight them clearly.

\#\# Output Format

Produce a single Markdown assignment handout that students can read directly. Include a short Assumptions section only when needed.

\#\# Resources

\- \`references/course-files.md\` for the syllabus and HW1 locations.  
\- \`references/assignment-template.md\` for the draft skeleton.

# **Appendix 2: Benchmark Methods**

There is no single industry standard for evaluating agentic systems. Most teams use a combination of methods depending on scale, risk, and time. Below are common approaches you can choose from.

### **1\) Human Rubric Scoring**

Small test set, scored by a human using a clear rubric with anchors. This is often treated as the gold standard for quality on a limited set of cases.

### **2\) LLM-as-Judge**

Use an LLM to score outputs against a rubric. Often used for rapid regression testing, but should be calibrated against human judgment.

### **3\) Baseline Comparison (A/B)**

Compare your system against a baseline such as a single-prompt LLM, manual workflow, or previous version. Focuses on relative improvement.

### **4\) Regression Test Suites**

Fixed test cases that you re-run after changes to prompts, tools, or workflows to check for drift.

### **5\) Edge-Case Testing**

Intentionally difficult or ambiguous inputs to surface failure modes and safety issues early.

### **6\) Operational Metrics**

Latency, cost per output, error rate, escalation rate, and other operational stats.

*For this course, any of the above methods are acceptable. Choose what best fits your workflow and explain your choice clearly.*
